<!-- WHY DIFFERENT -->
<section class="sec"><div class="ctr">
  <div class="badge badge-dark">WHY BOOKS NEED SPECIALIZED LOGISTICS</div>
  <h2 class="sec-h2">Six things that break book e-commerce logistics on a self-operated warehouse</h2>
  <div class="bk-prob-grid">
    <div class="bk-prob-card">
      <h3>Large title catalog with low per-SKU velocity</h3>
      <p>A typical publisher operates 500-3,000 active titles, of which 80% are long-tail with sales of 1-3 copies per month. On a self-operated warehouse this means a packer spending half an hour searching for a rare book among the shelves. In our setup each ISBN is bound to a specific cell address in the WMS. Manual searching is eliminated — the system routes the picker to the shelf, and assembling a 3-4 book order takes 47 seconds end-to-end.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bk-prob-card">
      <h3>Low AOV requires transparent unit pricing</h3>
      <p>Average order value in book e-commerce is $7-17, and retailer margin is 15-25%. On a $9 order with 20% margin, the publisher captures roughly $1.80 of gross profit before logistics. Every cent of fulfilment cost is critical here. Our model is linear $0.41 per shipment from 200+ orders per day volume, with no hidden handling fee, peak surcharge, or platform fee. The number on your quote equals the number on your monthly invoice.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bk-prob-card">
      <h3>September school season and Christmas peaks break self-operated warehouses</h3>
      <p>The Ukrainian book market lives in two peaks: August-September (textbooks, school literature, children's books) and November-December (Black Friday, holiday gifts, corporate orders). During these weeks order volume grows 3-7 times over baseline. A self-operated warehouse with two packers cannot keep up. Our facility handles up to 6,000 orders per day with automatic capacity scaling through additional shifts at no upcharge in the per-order rate.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bk-prob-card">
      <h3>Damage in transit kills brand perception</h3>
      <p>Books — especially gift editions and art books — easily suffer bent cover corners, spine creases, or moisture damage from negligent packaging. Standard polyethylene mailers from carriers do not address this. We package using bubble wrap around the book, then a rigid book-format cardboard mailer (B5 for standard, A4 for oversize). For gift editions and art books we add a kraft paper layer. The damage-related return rate drops from an industry-typical 3-5% to roughly 0.4%.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bk-prob-card">
      <h3>Print run tracking and ISBN error prevention</h3>
      <p>Publishers frequently reissue a title with a changed ISBN (new edition, corrections) — and the warehouse retains residual inventory of the old run. Our WMS surfaces both ISBNs separately, applies FEFO logic by print date, and never silently mixes runs during pick. If a customer orders the new edition but only old-run copies remain, the system alerts the publisher for a routing decision rather than shipping the wrong ISBN.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bk-prob-card">
      <h3>Cross-border export to diaspora markets</h3>
      <p>Ukrainian literature ships actively to diaspora readers in Poland, Czechia, Germany, Canada, and the USA. This channel does not work with standard fulfilment workflows. We prepare CN23 customs forms (books carry 0% import duty in most destination countries), handle export documentation, and hand off to NP International express delivery. A reader in Warsaw receives the book in 5-7 days; in Toronto, 14-21 days. The publisher does not touch documentation per shipment.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div></section>

<!-- USE CASES -->
<section class="sec sec-alt"><div class="ctr">
  <div class="badge badge-dark">WHO WE WORK WITH</div>
  <h2 class="sec-h2">Four book client profiles we serve</h2>
  <p style="font-size:18px;margin-top:24px;max-width:900px">Books fulfilment covers four distinct business models. Each gets its own pricing tier and operational angle.</p>
  <div class="bk-uc-grid">
    <div class="bk-uc-card">
      <h3>1. Self-published authors</h3>
      <p>Bloggers, subject-matter experts, children's illustrators printing 50-500 copies of their own book. Selling through Instagram, Telegram, their own Shopify or Squarespace site, sometimes through Yakaboo as an external sales channel. No warehouse, no logistics team. They ship the print run to us; we accept orders from all channels and dispatch. Monthly minimum of $114 — breaks even at approximately 250 orders per month or a series of B2B pre-orders for the same title.</p>
      <p><strong>Typical profile:</strong> 1-3 titles, 100-500 copies per run, 100-300 orders per month, AOV $8-11.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bk-uc-card">
      <h3>2. Small and mid-size publishers</h3>
      <p>Independent publishers with 50-1,000 active titles and no internal infrastructure team. Often focused on niche segments: translations from rare languages, specialized literature, religious editions, children's literature. Switch to outsourced fulfilment after their own warehouse stops scaling efficiently — typically around 500 orders per month.</p>
      <p><strong>Typical profile:</strong> 100-1,500 active catalog titles, 1,000-5,000 orders per month, AOV $9-17, predominantly DTC plus Rozetka and Prom as secondary channels.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bk-uc-card">
      <h3>3. B2B corporate and educational orders</h3>
      <p>Corporations purchasing 50-500 copies of a single title for employees, clients, partners, or educational programs. High AOV ($375-5,000 per order), low order count (5-30 per month), but stable margins and effectively zero return rate. We handle these with personalized assembly, branded packaging from the corporate buyer, and delivery to office addresses or multiple recipient addresses simultaneously.</p>
      <p><strong>Typical profile:</strong> 1-10 titles (typically bestsellers or business books), 5-30 orders per month, AOV $375-5,000.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bk-uc-card">
      <h3>4. Cross-border export to diaspora markets</h3>
      <p>Diaspora readership in Poland, Czechia, Germany, Canada, and the USA reads Ukrainian literature and is willing to order directly from Ukraine. Publishers like Stary Lev, Vivat, Vydavnytstvo 21 export through us with CN23 customs documentation, NP International dispatch, and local card-payment partners. Separate cross-border pricing tier — each parcel is calculated by weight and destination country.</p>
      <p><strong>Typical profile:</strong> 50-500 cross-border parcels per month, AOV $25-80 in EUR or USD, primary destinations PL/DE/CZ/CA/US.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div></section>

<!-- HOW IT WORKS -->
<section class="sec"><div class="ctr">
  <div class="badge badge-dark">PROCESS</div>
  <h2 class="sec-h2">How book fulfilment works — 8 operational steps</h2>
  <div class="bk-steps">
    <div class="bk-step"><div class="bk-step-num">1</div><div class="bk-step-body"><h3>Print run intake by ISBN</h3><p>You ship the print run to our warehouse in Shchaslyve (2,700 m²) or Bilohorodka (1,000 m²). Each title is scanned by ISBN barcode from the cover and bound to a specific shelf cell. We verify counts against the print run record — if 500 copies were declared but 487 arrived, the variance is logged immediately. The intake report appears in your WMS dashboard within 24 hours.</p></div></div>
    <div class="bk-step"><div class="bk-step-num">2</div><div class="bk-step-body"><h3>Shelf placement</h3><p>Books are stored vertically on book-format shelves (35-40 cm height for most editions). Art books and gift editions go horizontally in stacks of 5-10. High-velocity titles get prime ground-floor shelves; long-tail titles go higher. Address-based system: each shelf has a code, each title has a fixed cell. No manual searching required during pick.</p></div></div>
    <div class="bk-step"><div class="bk-step-num">3</div><div class="bk-step-body"><h3>Storefront integration</h3><p>Orders from Horoshop, KeyCRM, SalesDrive, WooCommerce, OpenCart, Shopify, Magento, Prom.ua, Rozetka — all flow into our WMS automatically via API. Prebuilt connectors deploy in 2 hours. For non-standard platforms — webhook or CSV import. Inventory syncs between your storefront and our WMS in real time at 800 ms latency.</p></div></div>
    <div class="bk-step"><div class="bk-step-num">4</div><div class="bk-step-body"><h3>Order assembly</h3><p>WMS builds an optimal pick path through the warehouse. Scanner guides the picker to each shelf; the operator verifies ISBN before pickup. A 1-2 book order assembles in 30-45 seconds, a 3-5 book order in 60-90 seconds. Accuracy is double-verified at the pack station via re-scan. Pick accuracy of 99.5% means no more than 5 errors per 1,000 orders.</p></div></div>
    <div class="bk-step"><div class="bk-step-num">5</div><div class="bk-step-body"><h3>Damage-resistant packaging</h3><p>Standard book packaging: bubble wrap around the cover, then rigid book-format cardboard mailer (B5 for standard editions, A4 for oversize). The spine sits in the middle of the mailer to absorb transit impact. Gift editions and art books receive an additional kraft paper layer and branded ribbon. Multi-book orders go in MTP-branded box or your custom-branded packaging with paper void-fill so books do not collide.</p></div></div>
    <div class="bk-step"><div class="bk-step-num">6</div><div class="bk-step-body"><h3>Carrier handoff</h3><p>Four Nova Poshta pickups per day at 10:00, 12:00, 15:00, and 17:00. Orders placed before 14:00 ship same-day; the buyer in Kyiv receives an SMS by evening. For cross-border export — separate NP International channel with CN23 customs documentation. Ukrposhta serves regional addresses in small cities not covered by Nova Poshta network.</p></div></div>
    <div class="bk-step"><div class="bk-step-num">7</div><div class="bk-step-body"><h3>Returns processing</h3><p>Return arrives at warehouse → unpacked → photographed → inspected for damage. Books in good condition return to shelf inventory automatically within 24 hours. Damaged copies or copies with reading marks go to a dedicated zone for publisher decision. Return processing fee of $0.57 per unit with photo documentation — critical for resolving customer disputes ('the cover was perfect when shipped, here is the photo from departure').</p></div></div>
    <div class="bk-step"><div class="bk-step-num">8</div><div class="bk-step-body"><h3>Reporting and analytics</h3><p>WMS dashboard shows real-time inventory by ISBN, movement history of each copy, order volume by day/week/month, return rate per title, projected stock-out for each print run. For accounting — month-end reconciliation report generates automatically with all line items: shipments, storage, returns, packaging extras. No 'we will reconcile at quarter end' surprises.</p></div></div>
  </div>
</div></section>

<!-- PRICING -->
<section class="sec sec-alt"><div class="ctr">
  <div class="badge badge-dark">PRICING</div>
  <h2 class="sec-h2">How much book fulfilment costs at MTP</h2>
  <p style="font-size:18px;margin-top:24px;max-width:900px">Transparent rate card with linear pricing. No peak season surcharge, fuel adjustment, or other industry-standard inventions for invisible cost inflation.</p>
  <div class="bk-pricing">
    <table class="bk-price-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Service</th><th>Tier</th><th>Price</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Per-shipment fee</td><td>200+ orders/day</td><td>from $0.41</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Per-shipment fee</td><td>50-199 orders/day</td><td>from $0.50</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Per-shipment fee</td><td>10-49 orders/day</td><td>from $0.59</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Storage</td><td>per m³/month</td><td>$15</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Print run intake</td><td>per unit</td><td>from $0.07</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Returns with photo</td><td>per return</td><td>$0.57</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cross-border (NP International)</td><td>quoted individually</td><td>by weight + destination</td></tr>
        <tr class="highlight"><td>Monthly minimum</td><td>any volume</td><td>$114</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="bk-price-note" style="margin-top:24px;font-size:16px;color:#666">Pricing scales down with volume. Custom quote for your specific average order value, title count, and geographic distribution arrives within one business day after the first 15-minute consultation. Our commercial proposal template fits on a single A4 page with three line items.</p>
  </div>
</div></section>

<!-- SEASONALITY -->
<section class="sec"><div class="ctr">
  <div class="badge badge-dark">SEASONALITY</div>
  <h2 class="sec-h2">September school season, Black Friday, Christmas — how we prepare for peaks</h2>
  <p style="font-size:18px;margin-top:24px;max-width:900px">The Ukrainian book market lives in two peaks. A self-operated warehouse with two packers cannot keep up. Our facility handles peaks structurally without emergency hiring.</p>
  <p><strong>August-September — back-to-school surge.</strong> Textbooks, school literature, children's books, learning materials for first graders. Volume for a typical publisher grows 3-5 times over July baseline. We meet with each client four weeks before September 1 to plan volume, replenish packaging stock, schedule additional shifts. After the peak we return to baseline operations without surcharge.</p>
  <p><strong>November — Black Friday.</strong> Discounts on bestsellers, promotions on children's literature, holiday gift bundles. Volume grows 4-7 times over baseline. Often a separate logistics flow for gift packaging — branded boxes from the publisher, holiday ribbons, greeting cards. These are additional operations that need to be planned in advance. We calculate the peak rate including custom operations before the season starts.</p>
  <p><strong>December — Christmas corporate orders.</strong> Corporations purchase 50-500 copies of a single title for employees and clients. High AOV, low order count, large per-order assembly. A separate WMS queue for B2B orders prevents mixing with the DTC stream. December 2024 peak averaged 9,200 orders per day across our client base with zero downtime in fulfilment execution.</p>
  <p><strong>January-May — low season.</strong> Between peaks the book market dips. Self-operated warehouses idle in this period — packers' salaries are paid, rent is paid, but volume is half of peak. Our pricing scales proportionally with volume: fewer orders, smaller invoice. Unit economics become elastic. This is the difference between 'sell our own warehouse at a loss' and 'comfortably ride out the low season'.</p>
</div></section>

<!-- CROSS-BORDER -->
<section class="sec sec-alt"><div class="ctr">
  <div class="badge badge-dark">INTERNATIONAL EXPORT</div>
  <h2 class="sec-h2">Cross-border export of Ukrainian literature to diaspora markets</h2>
  <p style="font-size:18px;margin-top:24px;max-width:900px">Ukrainian diaspora communities in Poland, Czechia, Germany, Canada, and the USA represent active book-buying audiences willing to order directly from Ukraine. This channel is not covered by standard fulfilment workflows — it requires a separate documentation pipeline.</p>
  <p><strong>CN23 customs declaration preparation.</strong> Every international shipment requires a CN23 customs form describing contents. Books carry 0% import duty in most destination countries (Poland, Czechia, Germany, Canada, USA), but the form is still mandatory. We generate CN23 automatically using order data; the publisher does not need to fill out customs documentation per shipment.</p>
  <p><strong>Delivery channels.</strong> Primary channel is Nova Poshta International. Transit times: Poland 5-7 business days, Germany 7-10, Czechia 6-8, Canada 14-21, USA 14-25. Pricing depends on weight and country. For heavy multi-book orders or art-book shipments — alternative channel via Meest for select destinations with lower per-weight rates.</p>
  <p><strong>Currency and settlement.</strong> Cross-border buyers pay in EUR or USD. For the publisher this introduces FX exposure on the cost side. Our cross-border quote applies the monthly average NBU reference rate transparently to every line item, so the publisher sees per-shipment cost in both UAH and the buyer's local currency.</p>
  <p><strong>Publisher case patterns.</strong> Stary Lev regularly exports children's literature to Poland and Czechia. Vydavnytstvo 21 exports English-language and Ukrainian books to Canada. Smaller publishers releasing historical literature export to Germany and the USA. Cross-border is not for everyone — but for niche publishers with diaspora audiences, this channel represents a meaningful 5-15% of annual revenue.</p>
</div></section>

<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="sec"><div class="ctr">
  <div class="badge badge-dark">FAQ</div>
  <h2 class="sec-h2">Frequently asked questions about book fulfilment</h2>
  <div class="bk-faq">
    <details><summary>How much does book fulfilment cost at 30 orders per day?</summary><p>Approximately $320-410 per month. Calculation: shipping $0.50 × 900 orders = $450, but with low-AOV book volume discount drops to ~$0.36. Storage 1 m³ × $15 = $15. Exact figure delivered within one business day after the first 15-minute consultation.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How do you track books — by ISBN or by internal SKU?</summary><p>Both simultaneously. ISBN is primary identifier bound to shelf cell. Publisher's internal SKU stored as alias. At intake we scan ISBN from cover, assign to fixed shelf address.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Do you accept small print runs from self-published authors?</summary><p>Yes. Minimum print run is 20 copies per title. We work with self-published authors printing 50-500 copies. Separate pricing tier for low-volume operations, $114 monthly minimum.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How do you package books to prevent corner damage?</summary><p>Bubble wrap around book, then rigid book-format cardboard mailer (B5 or A4). For gift editions — additional kraft paper layer. Multi-book orders go in branded box with paper void-fill.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How do you prepare for September school season and Black Friday peaks?</summary><p>Four weeks before each peak we plan volume, replenish packaging stock, schedule additional shifts. Capacity up to 6,000 orders/day. December 2024 peak averaged 9,200 orders/day across client base.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Do you handle cross-border shipping to Poland and Canada?</summary><p>Yes, via Nova Poshta International. We prepare CN23 customs forms. Transit: Poland 5-7 days, Canada 14-21 days. Pricing by weight and country.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How do you process book returns?</summary><p>Unpack → photograph → inspect for damage. Good-condition copies return to shelf inventory within 24 hours. Damaged copies go to dedicated publisher-decision zone. Fee $0.57 with photo documentation.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Do you integrate with Horoshop and KeyCRM?</summary><p>Yes, natively. Prebuilt connector deploys in 2 hours. Orders flow into WMS automatically; status returns to your store admin. Also supports WooCommerce, OpenCart, Shopify, Magento, Prom.ua API, Rozetka API.</p></details>
